===Education and Gender===
[[Image:Education Income.jpg|thumb|550px|This graph shows the median household income in accordance with the householder's educational attainment. The data only applies to household with a householder over the age of twenty-five.<ref name="Educational attainment and median household income">{{cite web|url=http://www.census.gov/hhes/income/histinc/h13.html|title=Educational attainment and median household income|accessdate=2006-09-24}}</ref>]]
Household income as well as per capita income in the [[United States]] rise significantly as the [[Educational attainment in the United States|educational attainment]] increases.<ref name="US Census Bureau, Income by education and sex">{{cite web|url=http://www.census.gov/hhes/income/earnings/call1usboth.html|title=US Census Bureau, Income by education and sex|accessdate=2006-06-30}}</ref> In 2005 graduates with a [[MBA|Master's in Business Administration]] (MBA) who accepted job offers are expected to earn a base salary of $88,626. They are also expected to receive "…[a]n average [[signing bonus]] of $17,428."<ref name="Wall Street Journal on MBA salary base">{{cite web|url=http://www.collegejournal.com/salarydata/mba/mbas.html|title=Wall Street Journal on MBA salary base|accessdate=2006-06-30}}</ref> According to the [[US Census Bureau]] persons with [[Educational attainment in the United States|doctorates]] in the United States had an average income of roughly $81,400. The average for an advanced degree was $72,824 with men averaging $90,761 and women averaging $50,756 annually. Year-round full-time workers with a [[Educational attainment in the United States|professional degree]] had an average income of $109,600 while those with a  [[Educational attainment in the United States|Master's degree]] had an average income of $62,300. Overall "…[a]verage earnings ranged from $18,900 for [[Educational attainment in the United States|high school dropouts]] to $25,900 for [[Educational attainment in the United States|high school graduates]], $45,400 for [[Educational attainment in the United States|college graduates]] and $99,300 for workers with [[Educational attainment in the United States|professional degrees]] (M.D., D.O., J.D., D.D.S., or D.V.M.). <ref name="US Census Bureau on Education and Income">{{cite web|url=http://www.census.gov/prod/2002pubs/p23-210.pdf|title=US Census Bureau on Education and Income|accessdate=2006-06-30}}</ref> 

Considering how education significantly enhances the earnings potential of individuals, it should come as no surprise that individuals with [[graduate degree]]s have an average [[per capita income]] exceeding the [[median household income]] of [[Census family|married couple families]] among the general population ($63,813).<ref name="US Census Bureau on Education and Income">{{cite web|url=http://www.census.gov/prod/2002pubs/p23-210.pdf|title=US Census Bureau on Education and Income|accessdate=2006-06-30}}</ref><ref name="Infoplease, median household income">{{cite web|url=http://www.infoplease.com/ipa/A0104688.html|title=Infoplease, median household income|accessdate=2006-06-29}}</ref>  Higher [[Educational attainment in the United States|educational attainment]] did not, however, help close the income gap between the genders as the life-time earnings for a male with a professional degree were roughly forty percent (39.59%) higher than those of a female with a [[Educational attainment in the United States|professionals degree]].  The life-time earnings gap between males and females was the smallest for those individuals holding an [[Educational attainment in the United States|Associate degrees]] with male life-time earnings being 27.77% higher than those of females. While [[educational attainment]] did not help reduce the [[income inequality]] between men and women, it did increase the earnings potential of individuals of both sexes, greatly enabling many households with (a) [[Educational attainment in the United States|graduate degree]] householder(s) to enter the top household income quintile.<ref name="US Census Bureau on Education and Income">{{cite web|url=http://www.census.gov/prod/2002pubs/p23-210.pdf|title=US Census Bureau on Education and Income|accessdate=2006-06-30}}</ref>

Household income also increased significantly with the [[Educational attainment in the United States|educational attainment]] of the householder. The [[US Census Bureau]] publishes [[Educational attainment in the United States|educational attainment]] and income data for all households with a householder who was aged twenty-five or older. The biggest income difference was between those with some college education and those who had a [[Bachelor's degree]], with the latter making $23,874 more. Income also increased substantially with increased post-secondary education. While the median household income for a household with a household holding an Associates degree was $51,970, the median household income for those with a Bachelor's degree or higher was $73,446. Those with [[Doctorate degree|doctorates]] had the second highest median household with a median of $96,830; $18,289 more higher than that for those at the [[Master's degree]] level, but $3,170 lower than the median for households with a professionals degree holding householder.<ref name="Educational attainment and median household income">{{cite web|url=http://www.census.gov/hhes/income/histinc/h13.html|title=Educational attainment and median household income|accessdate=2006-09-24}}</ref>

