'''SOURCE: US Census Bureau, 2005/06'''<ref name="US Census Bureau, median household income by state 2006">{{cite web|url=http://www.census.gov/hhes/www/income/income06/statemhi2.html|title=US Census Bureau, median household income by state 2006|accessdate=2007-10-13}}</ref>

==Median income==
The [[median]] income divides households in the US evenly in the middle with half of all household earning more than the median income and half of all households earning less than the median household income. In 2004 the median household income in the [[United States]] was $43,389.<ref name="Infoplease, median household income">{{cite web|url=http://www.infoplease.com/ipa/A0104688.html|title=Infoplease, median household income|accessdate=2006-06-29}}</ref> According to the [[US Census Bureau]], the median is "considerably lower than the average, and provides a more accurate representation."<ref name="US Census Bureau on the nature the median in determining wealth">{{cite web|url=http://www.census.gov/prod/2003pubs/p70-88.pdf|title=US Census Bureau on the nature the median in determining wealth|accessdate=2006-06-29}}</ref> Considering other racial and geographical differences in regards to household income, it should come as no surprise that the [[median]] household income varies with [[race]], size of household and [[geography]]. The [[US state|state]] with the highest median household income in the United States as of the US Census Bureau 2005/06 is [[New jersey]] with $66,752, followed by [[Maryland]], [[Hawaii]] and [[Connecticut]], making the [[Northeastern United States]] the wealthiest area by income in the entire country.<ref name="US Census Bureau, median household income by state">{{cite web|url=http://www.census.gov/hhes/www/income/income04/statemhi.html|title=US Census Bureau, median household income by state|accessdate=2006-06-29}}</ref> In terms of region the median household income was as follows: "[[Northeastern United States|Northeast]] ($47,994), [[Western United States|West]] ($47,680) and [[Southern United States|South]] ($40,773)." Median household income in the [[Midwestern United States|Mid-West]] declined by 2.8% to $44,657.<ref name="US Census Bureau, median household income according to certain demographic characteristics">{{cite web|url=http://www.census.gov/Press-Release/www/releases/archives/income_wealth/005647.html|title=US Census Bureau, median household income according to certain demographic characteristics|accessdate=2006-06-29}}</ref> While median household income has a tendency to increase up to four persons per household, it declines thereon after. This indicated that while four person households have larger incomes than those with one, two or three members, households seem to earn progressively less as their size increases beyond four persons. According to the US Census Bureau 2004 Community Survey, two-person households had a median income of $39,755, with $48,957 for three-person households, $54,338 for four-person households, $50,905 for five-person households, $45,435 for six-person households, with seven-or-more-person households having the second lowest median income of only $42,471.<ref name="US Census Bureau, median family income by family size">{{cite web|url=http://www.census.gov/hhes/www/income/medincsizeandstate.html|title=US Census Bureau, median family income by family size|accessdate=2006-06-29}}</ref>. In terms of race, [[Asian-Americans]] households had the highest median household income of $57,518, [[European-American]] households ranked second with $48,977, [[Hispanic|Hispanic or Latino]] households ranked third with $34,241. [[African-American|African American or Black]] households had the lowest median household income of all races with $30,134.<ref name="US Census Bureau, median household income according to certain demographic characteristics">{{cite web|url=http://www.census.gov/Press-Release/www/releases/archives/income_wealth/005647.html|title=US Census Bureau, median household income according to certain demographic characteristics|accessdate=2006-06-29}}</ref>

==Mean income==<!-- This section is linked from [[Social class]] -->
Another common measurement of personal income is the mean household income. Unlike the median household income which divides all households in two halves, the mean income is the average income earned by [[United States|American]] households. In the case of mean income, the income of all households is divided by the number of all households.<ref name="US Government, the different between mean and median">{{cite web|url=http://www.business.gov/topics/research_resources/market_research/census_bureau_faq.html|title=US Government, the different between mean and median|accessdate=2006-06-29}}</ref> The mean income is usually more affected by the relatively unequal distribution of income which tilts towards the top.<ref name="US Census Bureau on the nature the median in determining wealth">{{cite web|url=http://www.census.gov/prod/2003pubs/p70-88.pdf|title=US Census Bureau on the nature the median in determining wealth|accessdate=2006-06-29}}</ref> As a result the mean tends to be higher than the median income with the top earning households boosting it. Overall the mean household income in the United States according to the [[US Census Bureau]] 2004 Economic Survey was $60,528, or $17,210 (39.73%) higher than the median household income.<ref name="US Census Bureau, mean household income">{{cite web|url=http://pubdb3.census.gov/macro/032005/hhinc/new06_000.htm|title=US Census Bureau, mean household income|accessdate=2006-06-29}}</ref>

{{cquote|
"[[Median]] income is the amount which divides the [[income distribution]] into two equal groups, half having income above that amount, and half having income below that amount. [[Mean]] income ([[average]]) is the amount obtained by dividing the total aggregate income of a group by the number of units in that group. The means and medians for households and families are based on all households and families. Means and medians for people are based on people 15 years old and over with income."<ref name="US Government, the different between mean and median">{{cite web|url=http://www.business.gov/topics/research_resources/market_research/census_bureau_faq.html|title=US Government, the different between mean and median|accessdate=2006-06-29}}</ref><br>-US Census Bureau, Frequently Asked Question, published by First Gov.
}}

The mean household income for households headed by persons identifying as [[White (people)|White alone]] was $65,317, $40,685 for those headed by persons identifying as [[African American|African American or Black]], $45,871 for those headed by persons identifying as [[Hispanic|Hispanic or Latino]], and $76,747 for those households headed by persons identifying as [[Asian-Americans|Asian alone]]. Approximately one third, or 36.5%, of all households earned more than the mean income, while 63.5% earned less than the mean.<ref name="US Census Bureau, mean household income">{{cite web|url=http://pubdb3.census.gov/macro/032005/hhinc/new06_000.htm|title=US Census Bureau, mean household income|accessdate=2006-06-29}}</ref>

